import os
import pandas as pd
import shutil
import random

random.seed(123)


# Define paths
csv_file_path = '/home/noni/Documents/gun_vio/clustering_results_relevant.csv'
image_folder_path = '/home/noni/Documents/gun_vio/FirstBatch'
output_folder_path = '/home/noni/Documents/gun_vio/clusters'

# Create the output directory if it doesn't exist
if not os.path.exists(output_folder_path):
    os.makedirs(output_folder_path)

# Load the CSV with clustering results
df = pd.read_csv(csv_file_path)

# Loop over each unique cluster label (0 to 6)
for cluster_label in df['Cluster Label'].unique():
    # Get all image paths for the current cluster
    cluster_images = df[df['Cluster Label'] == cluster_label]['Image Path'].tolist()

    # Randomly select 50 images (or less if not enough images)
    selected_images = random.sample(cluster_images, min(50, len(cluster_images)))

    # Create a folder for the current cluster label if it doesn't exist
    cluster_folder = os.path.join(output_folder_path, str(cluster_label))
    if not os.path.exists(cluster_folder):
        os.makedirs(cluster_folder)

    # Copy selected images to the respective folder
    for image_path in selected_images:
        # Get the full image path
        full_image_path = os.path.join(image_folder_path, os.path.basename(image_path))
        
        # Copy the image to the cluster folder
        shutil.copy(full_image_path, cluster_folder)

    print(f'Copied {len(selected_images)} images to folder {cluster_folder}')

print("All images have been copied to respective folders.")

import os
import subprocess

# Define the output folder path
output_folder_path = '/home/noni/Documents/gun_vio/clusters'

# Loop through each cluster folder
for folder_name in os.listdir(output_folder_path):
    cluster_folder = os.path.join(output_folder_path, folder_name)

    # Check if it's a directory (for clusters 0-6)
    if os.path.isdir(cluster_folder):
        # Define the output montage file name
        montage_output = os.path.join(output_folder_path, f'cluster_{folder_name}_montage.png')
        
        # Create a montage (grid of thumbnails) for the images in the folder
        # The `convert` command will create a 5x10 grid of images (adjust grid size if needed)
        subprocess.run([
            'convert', 
            f'{cluster_folder}/*.jpg',  # Adjust if images are in a different format like png
            '-thumbnail', '100x100',  # Define thumbnail size
            '-tile', '5x10',  # Create a grid (5 columns and 10 rows)
            '-geometry', '+2+2',  # Add padding between images
            montage_output
        ])
        
        print(f"Thumbnail montage created for folder {folder_name}: {montage_output}")

print("All montages created.")

LDA for image description in general

import pandas as pd
import nltk
import re
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Download NLTK stopwords
nltk.download('stopwords')
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

# Load the CSV file
data = pd.read_csv('/home/noni/Documents/gun_vio/image_descriptions.csv')

# Clean the descriptions: Lowercase, remove punctuation, and tokenize
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

def clean_description(text):
    text = text.lower()  # Lowercase
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', text)  # Remove punctuation
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)  # Remove digits
    tokens = text.split()  # Tokenize
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word not in stop_words]  # Remove stopwords
    return ' '.join(tokens)

data['Cleaned Description'] = data['Description'].apply(clean_description)

# Vectorize the text data (bag-of-words)
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words='english')
dtm = vectorizer.fit_transform(data['Cleaned Description'])

# Fit the LDA model
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=7, random_state=42)  # 5 topics, adjust as needed
lda.fit(dtm)

# Display the top words in each topic
def display_topics(model, feature_names, num_top_words):
    for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(model.components_):
        print(f"Topic {topic_idx}:")
        print(" ".join([feature_names[i] for i in topic.argsort()[:-num_top_words - 1:-1]]))

num_top_words = 10
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
display_topics(lda, feature_names, num_top_words)

# Optional: Visualize the word frequency for each topic
def plot_top_words(model, feature_names, n_top_words, title):
    num_topics = model.components_.shape[0]  # Number of topics
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_topics, figsize=(num_topics * 3, 7), sharex=True)  # Adjust columns
    axes = axes.flatten()
    for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(model.components_):
        top_features_ind = topic.argsort()[:-n_top_words - 1:-1]
        top_features = [feature_names[i] for i in top_features_ind]
        weights = topic[top_features_ind]

        ax = axes[topic_idx]
        ax.barh(top_features, weights, height=0.7)
        ax.set_title(f'Topic {topic_idx}', fontdict={'fontsize': 15})
        ax.invert_yaxis()
        ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=12)
        for i in 'top right left'.split():
            ax.spines[i].set_visible(False)
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=20)
    plt.show()

plot_top_words(lda, feature_names, 10, 'Topics in LDA Model')
